    <section id="about">
        <h2>About</h2>
        <p>I am a Visiting Scholar at Johns Hopkins University and a Master's student in Cognitive Science at the École Normale Supérieure in Paris. I hold an MPhil from Sorbonne Université (Philosophy of Science, Knowledge and Mind, <em>mention très bien</em>) and a BA with Honors in Philosophy from Oberlin College.</p>
        <p>My research interests span explanation, language, mind, and fashion.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="research">
        <h2>Research</h2>
        <p>Recently, my research has clustered into three main areas.</p>

        <div class="research-area">
            <div class="area-number">I. Explanation & Why-Questions</div>
            <p>The first centers around the fact that explanations are answers to why questions. This area has proven to be an interesting intersection of philosophy of science and metaphysics (on the explanation side), which I studied during my MPhil at La Sorbonne, and language and cognitive science (on the why-questions side), which I am currently studying at the ENS.</p>
            <p>So far, most of the talks I've given in this area center around the semantics of explanation and why-questions—and some implications of the semantics for the metaphysics of time and for AI.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="research-area">
            <div class="area-number">II. Philosophy of Computational Neuroscience & AI</div>
            <p>A second interest of mine involves general questions about the philosophy of computational neuroscience and AI. For instance, I have some thoughts about inferring things about the computational structure of mind from empirical data about brain-model alignment.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="research-area">
            <div class="area-number">III. Meaning Beyond Language</div>
            <p>My third main interest is a bit broader, and has to do with following question: <em>How, generally speaking, can things have meaning?</em></p>
            <p>So far, this interest has taken the form of figuring out how fashion (which has many non-linguistic tokens) inheres meaning and communicates. This research has paired nicely with my more dilettantish interests in fashion and in music.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

